  "prompt": "When the hydronium-ion concentration of a solution is 1\u00d710\u221212 M , what is the pH of the solution?",
  "response": "Let's solve this step by step:\n\n1) Recall the definition of pH:\n   \u2022 pH = -log[H3O+]\n   \u2022 Where [H3O+] is the hydronium-ion concentration\n\n2) In this problem, [H3O+] = 1\u00d710\u221212 M\n\n3) Plug this into the pH equation:\n   \u2022 pH = -log(1\u00d710\u221212)\n\n4) Use the logarithm rule for exponents:\n   \u2022 pH = -(-12 log 1)\n   \u2022 pH = -(-12)\n   \u2022 pH = 12\n\nTherefore, the pH of the solution is 12.\n\nLet's double-check:\n\u2022 We know the hydronium-ion concentration is 1\u00d710\u221212 M\n\u2022 We took the negative log of this value\n\u2022 log(1\u00d710\u221212) = -12\n\u2022 -log(1\u00d710\u221212) = 12 \u2713\n\nThe answer is 12.",
